== First usage of the term ''Byzantine Empire'' ==

I'm removing these sentences:

:However, it was not until the mid-19th century that the term came into general use in the Western world. As regards the English historiography in particular, the first occasion of the "Byzantine Empire" appears in an 1857 work of [[George Finlay]] (''History of the Byzantine Empire from 716 to 1057'').<ref>{{harvnb|Rosser|2011|p=2}}.</ref>
:{{reflist}}

[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qU9lmX2xYlUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Rosser] says nothing of the kind on p. 2, though on p. xxxvii he calls that expression "modern".  A search on [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EPwvAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA356&dq=%22they+who+write+of+the+Byzantine+Empire%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiK1bWI86PJAhUDPhQKHTdpDDgQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=%22they%20who%20write%20of%20the%20Byzantine%20Empire%22&f=false Google Books] shows it to have been used since at least 1704, and it's also used by [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JcxTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA519&dq=inauthor:Gibbon+%22Byzantine+Empire%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJvcDr-qPJAhUEuhQKHfnADMwQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=inauthor%3AGibbon%20%22Byzantine%20Empire%22&f=false Gibbon], but all that's just OR. The OED doesn't have an entry for ''Byzantine Empire''. --[[User:Antiquary|Antiquary]] ([[User talk:Antiquary|talk]]) 11:36, 22 November 2015 (UTC)
:Well now, it seems that when I look at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AYpqikYr3Q8C&pg=PA2&dq=finlay+rosser+byzantine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiR8JHU_KPJAhUHsxQKHZd9BvIQ6AEIIDAA#v=onepage&q=finlay%20rosser%20byzantine&f=false the right edition of Rosser] he really does say that.  I'm restoring the first of the sentences I removed, though the second is clearly wrong, as I've shown. --[[User:Antiquary|Antiquary]] ([[User talk:Antiquary|talk]]) 12:01, 22 November 2015 (UTC)

